### Dealing with signs of abuse

The greatest danger is doing nothing, if you suspect abuse is taking place. You need to put aside getting it wrong, i.e. the suspicion or if you're not quite sure if abuse is occurring.

Powerful emotional blocks can also prevent people from considering that someone is being abused.

Doing nothing if you have concerns is not an option, because that is not fulfilling your duty of care.

You must not investigate, but instead must pass on concerns or disclosures to the appropriate person so that they can act to protect the individual concerned.

### Safeguarding policies

UK Athletics has safeguarding policies, as well as established reporting procedures and referral forms.

These and other key policies are available on the UK Athletics website.

### Barriers to recognising and reporting abuse

- Creating a fuss or spoiling a relationship built at the club
- Confusing signs of abuse or putting them down to something else
- Dismissing abuse because of your relationship with the alleged abuser
- Potential barriers to reports concerns of abuse, which are understandable but must be overcome
- Fearing the consequences, both in terms of being right or wrong

As a leader, need to be alert to the fact that abuse can and does happen.
Focus as a leader needs to be on individuals, in this context.
__Their safety, health and wellbeing is your primary concern.__

*** Other barriers

Be aware that young people may face barriers in disclosing abuse, for a variety of reasons.

- Feeling ashamed about the situation
- Concerned that the abuser will get into trouble or go to prison
- They may care for or love the abuser and see talking about it as a betrayal
- Worry about consequences for the club or coaches
- They may not recognise that what they are experiencing  is abuse

People who give their time to people and are caring and considerate can provide a means for people to get help.

### How to respond

This is what to do if someone confides in you as they are being abused.

- Be welcoming, even if the time is not convenient. They may not do so again and it will have take _a lot_ of courage.
- Find a quite place to talk where you won't be interrupted. However, this must not be somewhere where you are alone with the individual.
- Stay calm and listen carefully.
- Allow them to tell you at their own pace.
- Ask questions for clarification only.
- Communicate in a way that is appropriate for the person's age, preferred communication method and language.
- Reassure them, telling them you will do all you can to help. Explain what may happen next.
- If emergency help is required, don't delay.
- Make notes as soon as possible.
- Contact your club's welfare officer immediately.
  - If at an event, report to the event manager, to the club's welfare officer or directly to UK Athletics online via the _UKA Submit a concern function_.
- The welfare officer should then refer it to the Safeguarding Lead office in their home country or at UK Athletics.

### Reporting abuse and reporting procedures

Where there are concerns, this must be done in one of the following ways:

- Through your clubs welfare officer
- Always to _UK Athletics, via the submit a concern function_ or the person responsible in your country for safeguarding

Also contact the UKA safeguarding lead if their are allegations about a collegaue or you have had allegations raised against you.

### Good practice

- Being open and conducting all interactions with young people in a public place and with appropriate consent
- Avoiding situations where you are alone with one young person
- If you have to meet or lead/coach a young person, ensure it is conducted in an open environment and where full consent and emergency contact details have been provided
- Never travel alone with a young person and never share a room on your own with a young person
- Challenge bullying, harassment, foul or provocative language or controlling behaviour
- Never ignore bullying by anyone. Listen to and support the victim
- Treat people fairly and without favouritism
- Be friendly, open and ensuring that relationships are appropriate for someone in a position of power and trust
- Respecting all club members helps them take responsibiliy for their own development and decision making
- Avoid unnecessary physical contact.
- Ensure your run leader licence remains valid
- Adopting good practice ensures individual's welfare and protects you from wrongful allegations.

### Poor practice

- Engaging in rough, physical or provocative games
- Shouting coaching comments who they believe are not working hard enough
- Harassing and use of discrimninatory language
- Engaging in an intimate relationship with athletes
- A group of athletes ganging up on a new athlete or refusing to talk to the new athlete
- A coach taking a group of young people away to an event on their own

Many other examples of poor practice exist.

If any of the following occur, make a written note of the specifics of the incident and report it to another club leader. And also report it to your club welfare officer.

If it involves a young adult, also inform an appropriate adult.

- If you accidentally hurt a young person
- If a young person appears distressed
- If a young person appears to be sexually aroused by your actions
- If a young person misunderstands or misinterprets something you have done
